arXiv.abstract:
Assume that $f$ is a continuous transformation $f:S^1 	o S^1$. We consider here the cases where $f$ is either the transformation $f(z)=z^2$ or $f$ is a smooth diffeomorphism of the circle $S^1$. Consider a fixed continuous potential $	au:S^1=[0,1) 	o \mathbb{R}$, $
u\in \mathbb{R}$ and $\varphi:S^1 	o \mathbb{C}$ (a quantum state). The transformation $\hat F_{
u}$ acting on $\varphi:S^1 	o \mathbb{C}$, $\hat F_{
u}(\varphi) = \phi$, defined by $\displaystyle \phi(z) = \hat F_{
u} (\varphi(z)) = \varphi(f(z))e^{i
u	au(z)}$ describes a discrete time dynamical evolution of the quantum state $\varphi$. Given $S: \mathbb{R}	o \mathbb{R}$ we define the Lagrangian state $$\varphi_{x}^S(z) = \sum_{k\in\mathbb{Z}} e^{ rac{iS (z-k)}{\hbar}} e^{- rac{(z-k-x)^2}{4\hbar}}.$$ In this case $\hat F_{
u}(\varphi_{x}^S(z)) = \sum_{k\in\mathbb{Z}}e^{ rac{iS (f(z)-k)}{\hbar}}e^{- rac{(f(z)-k-x)^2}{4\hbar}}e^{i
u	au(z)}$. Under suitable conditions on $S$ the micro-support of $\varphi^S_x (z)$, when $\hbar 	o 0$, is $(x,S'(x))$. One of meanings of the semiclassical limit in Quantum Mechanics is to take $
u= rac{1}{\hbar}$ and $\hbar 	o 0$. We address the question of finding $S$ such that $\varphi^S_x$ satisfies the property: $  orall x$, we have that $\hat{F}_
u(\varphi^S_x)$ has micro-support on the graph of $y	o S'(y)$ (which is the micro-support of $\varphi^S_x$). In other words: which $S$ is such that $\hat{F}_
u$ leaves the micro-support of $\varphi^S_x$ invariant? This is related to a coboundary equation for $	au$, twist conditions and the boundary of the fat attractor.
